# Discord Channel Analysis: üí¨-discussion

## 1. Summary

This chat segment contains minimal technical discussion, primarily consisting of casual conversation and community concerns about Korean exchange delistings. 

**Key Technical/Project Discussions:**
- **Migration Issues**: Multiple users (XXI_Rapax, Dabel) reported problems with the ai16z to elizaOS token migration, including "max amount reached" errors and LP token migration complications. Users were directed to migration support channels.
- **Bazaar Protocol**: A GitHub commit for the Kamiyo Protocol was shared, with sb clarifying that "bazaar" is the decentralized marketplace application running on Jeju - described as "the appstore for agents."
- **Token Utility Concerns**: stoikol raised questions about elizaOS token utility within the ecosystem, questioning why it's not being used for payments or gas fees. FoRever_BIG clarified it wasn't built as a gas fee token. The community expressed confusion about the token's purpose beyond rewards.
- **Korean Exchange Delisting**: Extensive discussion about ai16z/elizaOS being delisted from Korean exchanges (Bithumb, Coinone, Korbit) due to DAXA (Digital Asset Exchange Alliance) decisions. Cited reasons include lack of transparency in rebranding procedures and failure to properly disclose material information. Trading support ends February 12, 2026; deposit/withdrawal ends March 12, 2026.

**Community Sentiment:**
The chat reveals frustration about token utility clarity and exchange delistings. Multiple users questioned the team's vision for token usage, with degenwtf repeatedly criticizing the lack of clear documentation about token utility and contract addresses on official channels.

## 2. FAQ

Q: Can I migrate my old ai16z tokens purchased before November 2025? (asked by XXI_Rapax) A: Unanswered - user was directed to migration support channels

Q: Why is elizaOS token not being used for payments or utility within the ecosystem? (asked by stoikol) A: It wasn't built to be used as gas fee; utility tokens give access to products/services inside a platform (answered by FoRever_BIG)

Q: Will Bithumb support the AI16Z to ELIZAOS token swap? (asked by KARA) A: Yes, Bithumb has already announced it will support the token swap (answered by FoRever_BIG)

Q: Does this mean elizaOS will be listed after ai16z delisting in February on Korean exchanges? (asked by KARA) A: Unanswered

Q: Do I need to pay for X API to use Eliza for finding stuff on X? (asked by Discostu) A: Unanswered

Q: What is the bazaar protocol shown in the GitHub commit? (asked by elizafan222) A: Bazaar is the decentralized marketplace application running on Jeju - the appstore for agents (answered by sb)

Q: How do I migrate SOL-AI16Z LP tokens from Raydium? (asked by Dabel) A: Unanswered - user was directed to migration support channels

Q: Why did Korean exchanges delist elizaOS? (asked by Majid) A: Due to lack of transparency in rebranding procedures and failure to properly disclose material information affecting token value (answered by Ï£ºÎãà)

# Discord Channel Analysis: üí¨-coders

## 1. Summary

The channel discussion centered around Eliza framework implementations, data collection strategies, and infrastructure decisions. Jin shared a BountyBoard project using Eliza and highlighted Foundation Capital's context graphs article, noting Eliza's strong data foundation for building context graphs. 

Key technical questions emerged around deployment and API access. Omid Sa inquired about database choices (Pglite vs PostgreSQL) for Eliza Cloud container deployments, with cjft confirming either option works. Discostu asked about X API requirements for scraping, questioning the $200/month cost versus alternative solutions within Eliza.

A significant portion of discussion focused on data collection and training strategies. DorianD proposed an Eliza Phone App concept for users to share data in exchange for reputation points and LLM training contributions. This evolved into discussions about the Jeju layer2 blockchain integration and innovative data collection methods using Inertial Motion Capture (IMocap) suits for various professions.

The conversation explored a novel economic model where workers wearing mocap suits during activities (fishing, haircutting, fast food preparation, even battlefield operations) could collect movement data. This data would be tokenized, allowing workers to earn royalties from AI inference when androids use their captured skills. The proposal suggested partnerships with employers like McDonald's to integrate mocap technology into uniforms.

Technical implementations were also discussed, including KamiyoAI's launch using the elizaos plugin. The babylon game experiment was mentioned as a data collection initiative. Infrastructure issues were noted with elizacloud.ai documentation being down.

## 2. FAQ

Q: For deploying in Elizacloud via containers should I use Pglite or PostgresSQL? (asked by Omid Sa) A: Either will work (answered by cjft)

Q: If I want to use eliza for X, helping me to find stuff on X, do I need to pay for X API or does eliza have something to help/scrap this without needing to pay $200/month? (asked by Discostu) A: Unanswered

Q: Does the KamiyoAI project make sense and are they using the elizaos plugin? (asked by elizafan222) A: Unanswered

## 3. Help Interactions

Helper: cjft | Helpee: Omid Sa | Context: Database choice for Eliza Cloud container deployment | Resolution: Confirmed either Pglite or PostgreSQL will work for the deployment

# Discord Chat Analysis - core-devs Channel

## 1. Summary

This brief chat segment contains limited technical discussion, primarily focusing on strategic observations about AI agent development and market dynamics.

**Key Discussion Points:**

Jin highlighted the project's strong data foundation for building AI agents that can serve as effective collaborators. The emphasis was on the quality of insights generated from agentic workflows across different time intervals (daily, weekly, monthly). The main technical gap identified is the integration of these high-quality insights into last-mile applications, specifically agents, webhooks, and apps.

Agent Joshua provided market analysis regarding inference markets, noting they are not particularly profitable based on observations from models offered on their platform and OpenRouter over the past year. This comment was made in response to a shared link about Fleek.

The conversation was minimal with no concrete technical implementations, code discussions, or architectural decisions made during this segment.

## 2. FAQ

No significant technical questions with meaningful responses were present in this chat segment.

## 3. Help Interactions

No help interactions occurred in this chat segment.
